oc:kn_03c3c720 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building any financial data pack" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Every number must trace to a source document with page reference. Use formula-based calculations exclusively — no hardcoded values. Verify balance sheet balances (Assets = Liabilities + Equity) and cash flow ties to balance sheet changes." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Zero tolerance for data errors — a single untraceable or hardcoded number undermines the entire deliverable's credibility with investment committees." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_0c607123 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When executing the complete data pack build" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Follow the 6-phase workflow: Phase 1 (extract from source documents), Phase 2 (normalize and standardize accounting), Phase 3 (build Excel workbook with xlsx skill), Phase 4 (build scenarios if projections exist), Phase 5 (quality control and validation), Phase 6 (final delivery with executive summary)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Sequential phase execution prevents rework — data extraction errors caught in Phase 2 are far cheaper to fix than formatting errors caught in Phase 5." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_0ef8f654 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing Excel formulas programmatically" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use hardcoded row offsets (e.g., row-15, row-19) in formulas. Always store row numbers in variables or a dictionary when writing data, then reference those stored variables in formulas." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Offset-based references break silently when table structure changes, are impossible to verify by reading code, and create debugging nightmares in delivered files." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_0ff01dcc a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting Phase 1 data extraction" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before building: identify fiscal year end date, locate 3-5 years of historical financials, identify management projections, flag data quality issues, and note all page references for traceability." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Missing fiscal year dates or unidentified data gaps cascade into structural errors that are expensive to fix later in the workflow." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_1fc0c544 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When applying cell formatting in Excel" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Font colors are mandatory: Blue (RGB: 0,0,255) for all hardcoded inputs, Black (RGB: 0,0,0) for all formulas/calculations, Green (RGB: 0,128,0) for cross-sheet links. Fill colors are optional unless user requests them." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Font color coding allows reviewers to instantly distinguish assumptions from calculations, which is standard practice in investment banking and private equity." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_21feacbe a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SideEffect ;
    oc:appliesToContext "During Phase 3 (Build Excel Workbook) and Phase 6 (Final Delivery)" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Creates a new Excel workbook file (.xlsx) in the outputs directory. Does not modify source documents." ;
    oc:hasRationale "File creation is the primary deliverable — ensure proper naming convention and output directory." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

oc:kn_4f9e4972 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:directiveContent """CompanyName_DataPack_YYYY-MM-DD.xlsx
  Tab 1: Executive Summary (1-page overview: company desc, 3-5 highlights, financial snapshot table)
  Tab 2: Historical Financials (Revenue by segment → COGS → Gross Profit → OpEx → EBITDA → Net Income)
  Tab 3: Balance Sheet (Current Assets → LT Assets → Current Li → LT Li → Equity, Assets=Li+Equity)
  Tab 4: Cash Flow (Operating → Investing → Financing → Net Change, indirect method)
  Tab 5: Operating Metrics (KPIs, unit volumes, productivity metrics — NO $ on counts)
  Tab 6: Property/Segment Performance (if applicable)
  Tab 7: Market Analysis (size, growth, competitive landscape, benchmarks)
  Tab 8: Investment Highlights (thesis, risks, management assessment)""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "CompanyName",
        "YYYY-MM-DD" .

oc:kn_569b5ff2 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When formatting any cell in the workbook" ;
    oc:directiveContent "RULE 1: Financial data → Currency format ($#,##0.0). RULE 2: Operational data → Number format (#,##0, NO $). RULE 3: Percentages → Percentage format (0.0%). RULE 4: Years → Text format to prevent comma insertion (2024 NOT 2,024). RULE 5: Mixed context → each metric gets its own format. RULE 6: All calculations must be formula-based." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Incorrect formatting (e.g., $ on store counts, commas in years, raw decimals for percentages) is immediately flagged as unprofessional by investment committee reviewers." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_60868616 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When making EBITDA normalization adjustments" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not add back restructuring charges if the company restructures every year. Do not add back ongoing integration investments. Assess whether 'one-time' charges are truly non-recurring before normalizing." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Aggressive normalization of recurring charges inflates EBITDA and creates credibility issues with investment committees. The Base Case should only include clearly non-recurring items." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_7f236d15 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PostFlightValidation ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before delivering the completed data pack" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Final checklist before delivery: verify all numbers trace to source, all calculations are formula-based, balance sheet balances, no formula errors (#REF!, #VALUE!, #DIV/0!), years display without commas, financial data has $, operational data has no $, percentages display as %, negatives use parentheses, filename follows CompanyName_DataPack_YYYY-MM-DD.xlsx convention." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Investment committee materials undergo intense scrutiny — any formatting or calculation error damages credibility of the entire analysis." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_88c80113 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting any data pack build" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Requires xlsx skill for all Excel file creation and manipulation. Source materials required: CIMs, offering memorandums, SEC filings, or access to web search / MCP server data." .

oc:kn_b1bb4839 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Complete data pack build workflow" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Analyze source data (identify financials, projections, fiscal year) → 2. Extract financial statements (IS, BS, CF with page refs) → 3. Extract operating metrics (KPIs, unit economics) → 4. Extract market data → 5. Normalize accounting (consistent line items, EBITDA reconciliation) → 6. Apply format detection per 6 rules → 7. Create adjustment schedule (document each normalization) → 8. Build 8-tab Excel workbook with xlsx skill → 9. Insert formula-based calculations (track row refs) → 10. Build scenarios (Management/Base/Downside) → 11. Run QC checklist → 12. Save as CompanyName_DataPack_YYYY-MM-DD.xlsx" ;
    oc:hasRationale "Ensures consistent, reproducible output that meets institutional standards for investment committee materials." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_be05af55 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing Excel formulas with openpyxl to maintain traceable cell references" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "python" ;
    oc:directiveContent """# Track row numbers as you write, then reference in formulas
revenue_row = row
write_data_row(ws, row, "Revenue", revenue_values)
row += 1
ebitda_row = row
write_data_row(ws, row, "EBITDA", ebitda_values)
row += 1
# Use stored row refs in formulas
margin_row = row
for col in year_columns:
    cell = ws.cell(row=margin_row, column=col)
    cell.value = f"={get_column_letter(col)}{ebitda_row}/{get_column_letter(col)}{revenue_row}"

# For complex models, use a dictionary:
row_refs = {'revenue': 5, 'cogs': 6, 'gross_profit': 7, 'ebitda': 12}
margin_formula = f"=B{row_refs['ebitda']}/B{row_refs['revenue']}\"""" .

oc:kn_cdb2984a a oc:Idempotency,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When re-running or updating an existing data pack" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Re-running the data pack build overwrites the previous workbook. Formula-based design means recalculations propagate automatically if source data changes, but the extraction phase must be re-executed to capture new data." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Formula-based architecture enables dynamic updates but the initial data extraction is always a fresh pull from source materials." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

oc:kn_daebb7c6 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When source materials include management projections" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Build three scenarios when projections are included: Management Case (company's projections as-is), Base Case (risk-adjusted with conservative adjustments), Downside Case (stress test for LBO/covenant analysis). Flag 'hockey stick' inflections requiring skepticism." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Three-scenario analysis is institutional standard for investment decisions — management cases are systematically optimistic and need risk-adjustment." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_e41ceb87 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating the workbook structure" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the standard 8-tab structure: Executive Summary, Historical Financials, Balance Sheet, Cash Flow Statement, Operating Metrics, Property/Segment Performance, Market Analysis, Investment Highlights." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Consistent tab structure enables investment committee members to navigate any data pack without orientation, creating institutional efficiency." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

